04543nam a22007095i 9786155211447DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222006hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97861552114477 a10.1515/97861552114472doi  a(DE-B1597)633454  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aJN96.A58bV36 2006 7aPOL0290002bisacsh04a320.94372221 aVanhuysse, Pieter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDivide and Pacify :bStrategic Social Policies and Political Protests in Post-Communist Democracies /cPieter Vanhuysse. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (190 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Tables -- tList of Figures -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgements -- tChapter 1 Introduction -- tChapter 2 The Unexpected Peacefulness of Transitions -- tChapter 3 Political Quiescence despite Conditions for Conflict -- tChapter 4 Preventing Protests: Divide and Pacify as Political Strategy -- tChapter 5 The Great Abnormal Pensioner Booms: Strategic Social Policies in Practice -- tChapter 6 Peaceful Pathways: The Political Economy of Post-Communist Welfare -- tChapter 7 Conclusions -- tReferences -- tIndex of Names -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite dramatic increases in poverty, unemployment, and social inequalities, the Central and Eastern European transitions from communism to market democracy in the 1990s have been remarkably peaceful. This book proposes a new explanation for this unexpected political quiescence. It shows how reforming governments in Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic have been able to prevent massive waves of strikes and protests by the strategic use of welfare state programs such as pensions and unemployment benefits. Divide and Pacify explains how social policies were used to prevent massive job losses with softening labor market policies, or to split up highly aggrieved groups of workers in precarious jobs by sending some of them onto unemployment benefits and many others onto early retirement and disability pensions. From a narrow economic viewpoint, these policies often appeared to be immensely costly or irresponsibly populist. Yet a more inclusive social-scientific perspective can shed new light on these seemingly irrational policies by pointing to deeper political motives and wider sociological consequences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aNew democraciesxEurope, Central. 0aNew democracieszEurope, Central. 0aPatronage, PoliticalxEurope, Central. 0aPatronage, PoliticalzEurope, Central. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh  aEconomic policy, Labor history, Patronage, Political economy, Protests, Sociology, Transition.1 aKornai, Janos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKornai, János, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978615521144740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9786155211447423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9786155211447/original  a978-3-11-078055-0  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998c1998d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK